g(x) = \frac{1}{2+x} ; a=1\\ \implies g(1)=\frac{1}{3}\\ \implies g^{'}(1)=\left(\frac{-1}{(2+1)^2}\right)=\frac{-1}{9}\\ \implies g^{(n)}(x)=\frac{(-1)^nn!}{(2+x)^{n+1}}\\ \implies g^{(n)}(1)=\frac{(-1)^nn!}{3^{n+1}}
g(x)=\sum^\infty_{n=0}\frac{g^{(n)}(1)}{n!}(x-1)^n\text{ about $1$.}\\ \implies g(x)=\sum^\infty_{n=0}\frac{(-1)^n}{3^{n+1}}(x-1)^n\text{ about $1$.}
